The sensitivity of the synthesized N-CQDs in detecting ampicillin was further examined, revealing a decrease in fluorescence intensity as the ampicillin concentration increased within the range of 0–10 ng/mL (Fig. 4A). The quenching mechanism responsible for this behaviour was attributed to the inner filter effect (IFE). The detection limit for ampicillin was determined to be 2.2 ng/mL (Fig. 4B). A comparison of various methods for ampicillin detection (Table 1
                        ) demonstrated that the developed sensor exhibited a superior detection limit compared to most reported methods. Only surface plasmon resonance (SPR) based methods showed a similar detection limit to the current study [31]. To evaluate the selectivity of N-CQDs, a constant concentration of different antibiotics was used, along with ampicillin. Interestingly, the fluorescence intensity of N-CQDs experienced a substantial reduction only in the presence of ampicillin. On the other hand, the fluorescence intensity remained largely unaffected in the presence of the other antibiotics (Fig. 5
                        ). This result indicates the accuracy of the biosensor in ampicillin detection.
